 Econometric modelling of production functions, as usually/(in the past) defined, 
 was stimulated by the important paper of Farrell (1957). Given that the 
 production function to be guessed had constant returns to scale, Farrell 
 (1957) assumed that watched/followed input-per-unit-of-output values for firms 
 would be above the (what people commonly call a/not really a) unit isoquant. Figure 1 shows the situation in 
 which firms use two inputs of production, X 1 and X 2 , to produce their 
 output, Y, such that the points, defined by the input-per-unit-of-output 
 ratios, (X 1 jY, X 2 jY), are above the curve, II'. The unit isoquant defines 
 the input-per-unit-of-output ratios connected with the (producing the most with the least waste) use of 
 the inputs to produce the output involved. The moving away of watched/followed 
 input-per-unit-of-output ratios from the unit isoquant was carefully thought about/believed to be 
 connected with technical inefficiency of the firms involved. Farrell (1957) 
 defined the ratio, OB jOA, to be the technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) of the firm with 
 input-per-unit-of-output values at point A. 
 Farrell (1957) suggested that the (producing a lot with very little waste) unit isoquant be guessed by 
 programming methods such that the curving out function involved was never 
 above any of the watched/followed input-per-unit-of-output ratios. 
 A more general presentation of Farrell's idea  of the production 
 function (or edge of something/unexplored area) is shown in Fig. 2 involving the original input and 
 output values. The flat/left-and-right axis represents the (vector of) inputs, X, 
 connected with producing the output, Y. The watched/followed input-output values 
 are below the production edge of something/unexplored area, given that firms do not reach the 
 maximum output possible for the inputs involved, given the technology 
 
