 output, y, with inputs, x, represented by point A, is given by y /Y *, where y * 
 is the 'frontier output' connected with the level of inputs, x (see point B). 
 This is a measure of technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) which is (may or may not happen, depending on something) on the levels 
 of the inputs involved. 
 The existence of technical inefficiency of firms working at production 
 has been a subject of large amounts of debate in money flow/money-based studies. For example, 
 Muller (1974) states (p. 731): "However, little is known about the role of 
 non-physical inputs, especially information or knowledge, which influence 
 the firm's ability to use its available technology set fully .... This suggests 
 how relative and (not made by nature/fake) the idea  of the edge of something/unexplored area itself is. . . . Once all 
 inputs are taken into account, measured working well differences should 
 disappear except for random disturbances. In this case the edge of something/unexplored area and the 
 average function are identical. They only diverge if significant inputs have 
 been left out in the guess". Upton (1979) also raised important 
 problems connected with scientific production function analysis. However, 
 (even though there is the existence of) these criticisms, we believe that the econometric modelling of 
 edge of something/unexplored area production functions, which is surveyed below, provides useful 
 ideas of best-practice technology and measures by which the productive (wasting very little while working or producing something) of different firms may be compared. 
 2. ECONOMETRIC MODELS 
 
 Production edge of something/unexplored area models are reviewed in three sub-sections involving 
 pre-decided edges of something/unexplored areas, (random/including random data points) edges of something/unexplored areas and panel data models. For 
 
