 3. EMPIRICAL APPLICATIONS 
 
 Edge of something/unexplored area production function models have been applied in a (large/relatively large) 
 number of scientific studies in farming-based money flow/money-based studies. (books, magazines, etc.) have 
 appeared in the all major farming-based money flow/money-based studies journals and a lot of other money-based journals. The Journal of Farming-based Money flow has published the most papers (at least seven, referred to below) dealing 
 with edge of something/unexplored area production functions. Other journals which have published at 
 least two applied production edge of something/unexplored area papers are the Canadian Journal of 
 Farming-based Money flow (4), the American Journal of Farming-based Money flow 
 (2) and the Southern Journal of Farming-based Money flow (2). At least one 
 edge of something/unexplored area production function paper involving farm-level data has appeared 
 in the Australian Journal of Farming-based Money flow, the (related to Europe) Review 
 of Farming-based Money flow, the North Central Journal of Farming-based Money flow and the Western Journal of Farming-based Money flow. A few papers 
 have appeared in development money flow/money-based studies journals as well as econometric 
 and other applied money flow/money-based studies journals. 
 The scientific studies are surveyed under the three headings involved in 
 the above section, depending on the type of edge of something/unexplored area production function 
 guessed. 
 
 3.1 
 
 Pre-decided edges of something/unexplored areas 
 
 Russell and Young (1983) guessed a pre-decided Cobb-Douglas 
 edge of something/unexplored area using corrected ordinary least-squares moving backward with a cross-sec- 
 
 FRONTIER PRODUCTION FUNCTIONS 
 
 195 
 
 tion of 56 farms in the North-West area of England during 1977-78. The 
 (thing that changes (like a test score) because of something else that you control (like study time)) was total money/money income received/got from the crop, animals and 
 miscellaneous activities on the farms involved. Technical (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) for 
 the individual farms were gotten using both the Timmer and Kopp 
 measures. 6 These two measures of technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) gave about 
 the same values and the same rankings for the 56 farms involved. The 
